[normal]In 1971 at decimalisation, my daily commute from Harrogate to Leeds was 0.34p for 36 miles of travel. Petrol was 0.34p per gallo
[normal]n, yes, gallon. The same rail journey to-day is £9.00 return but petrol is only £6.80 a gallon. To make matters worse, car parking in 1971 was free but now Northern charge £3 per day so effectively the daily rail commute is £12.00 nearly double the price o
[normal]f a gallon of petrol used in the same commuting distance. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Peak Car use was passed in 1997 falling to 2007 and has flat lined since. The Banking Crisis had nothing to do with the decline as it happened before the Crisis. It has more to do with high 
[normal]insurance costs for under 25 years old drivers and high cost of owning a car generally. Six Form students at Ripon Grammar School were asked what changes in Ripon would improve their lives the most in a survey by the Civic Society. Unprompted 72% wrote dow
[normal]n railway station.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]CONCLUSION
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I hope I have fully explained the case for reinstating Northallerton-Ripon-Harrogate-Wetherby-Cross gates and Wetherby-Tadcaster-Church Fenton. Primarily reinstatement 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]is to provide additional capacity but also can become a
[normal] passenger reconnection for the growing communities of Ripon, Wetherby and Tadcaster providing travel opportunities, increasing social inclusion and 
[normal]&#xa0;
